TY  - JOUR
AU  - Buchuk, David
AU  - Larrain, Borja
AU  - Prem, Mounu
AU  - Urzúa Infante, Francisco
T1  - How Do Internal Capital Markets Work? Evidence from the Great Recession*
PY  - 2020
Y1  - 2020/07/01
DO  - 10.1093/rof/rfz022
JO  - Review of Finance
JA  - Rev Financ
VL  - 24
IS  - 4
SP  - 847
EP  - 889
SN  - 1572-3097
AB  - We study the inner workings of internal capital markets during the 2008–09 recession using a unique dataset of loans between business group firms in an emerging market. Intragroup loans increase quickly during the recession. Firms that are more central in the ownership network simultaneously increase lending and borrowing. Acting like simple intermediaries, central firms do not increase net lending. Our results imply that formal control rights are essential for intermediation in internal capital markets, particularly during distress. In line with previous results on winner-picking, receivers of intragroup loans are high-Q, financially constrained firms, which also perform significantly better than providers during the recession.
Y2  - 3/26/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/rof/rfz022
ER  - 



